segments.text: No, no.
Drink, predominantly alcoholic would have been beer.
On the other side, it was Coca-Cola on this campus.
You couldn't go anywhere without running into a Coca-Cola vending machine.
Was Whiskey Bridge operating in those days?
No, sir.
I don't believe so.
It had already closed down.
I have no recollection of Whiskey Bridge.
other than from maybe the 60s when I heard stories about Ed's Hard Liquor.
He was down here and then Whiskey Bridge was over.
Was liquor by the drink legal yet in Brazos County?
Oh yes.
Margaritas and so forth?
No, I don't remember margaritas being a very popular drink.
I really don't know what the, piña coladas is what I remember.
And in terms of smoking, were you and your buddies even aware of the vocabulary of drugs and marijuana and so forth?
Were those words even known?
Yes, I probably was because of

the border uh atmosphere of drugs but uh even in laredo haskell i was not exposed to a drug culture or students who smoked pot or marijuana or cocaine or heroin did anybody here that you ever heard of let me tell you i i was at a lot of parties i was uh
I was in a lot of apartments, dorm rooms, cars, concerts, and yeah, I saw a few people smoking marijuana, but I never saw any cocaine, heroin, LSD, or drug sales or anything like that.
And the chicken ranch was long gone.
Long gone.
Just a myth to us.
I have not heard any Aggies talk anything about any kind of prostitution anywhere in Brazos County that they ever heard of, or bootleggers.
Now, there was a massage parlor called Lady T's or something like that out on Highway 6 on the way to Houston.
And some friends of mine said they had been there and that they were offered services beyond that of a massage parlor, but that's all I know.
All right.

As you look back, who were some people that if you had the capability to thank them personally for what they meant to you, who are some people who were here in whatever capacity that you now realize had an important effect on your life?
Well, I'd say Herb Thompson would be the first and foremost academically.
Edwin Cooper was a guy that was somewhat of a guardian angel, even though I didn't know it.
probably helped me get in and out of Texas A&M.
Frank Litterst was a guy that adopted me and just always I knew was there.
You know, he wasn't part of the campus per se, but A.W.

Head-Davis, a local attorney, was a classmate of my father's in the class of 45 and just felt like a security blanket, somebody I knew if I had trouble, particularly being an attorney, although I never needed him for anything.
And Buck Wyrus, of all people, who even as a nobody student encouraged me to come by and see him.
All right, for the sake of this machine, describe Buck Wyrus for somebody that might never have met him.
Buck Wyrus never met a stranger.
Never met a stranger.

um buck absolutely loved to talk about texas aggies now you've heard about people who and a lot of aggies are this way who love to talk about texas a m and i think that's that's admirable and it's true and it's accurate it's a big part of our culture but buck wirus in my
experience with him loved to talk about Texas Aggies.

I maintained a lifelong relationship with Buck until the day he died and had great respect for him and admiration for the network and the recollection and the intimate knowledge he had of Aggies worldwide.
It was just phenomenal.
And I never knew Buck, in my presence, to be down.
He always seemed upbeat, positive, energetic.
If Buck ever had a down day, I'm unaware of it.
And he had to have them in this role.
I know that.
I know that.
How did A&M, let's see, we got off on Buck.
Where are some other people that you remember with gratitude?
I mentioned Frank Litterst.
That's L-I-T-T-E-R-S-T.
Yes, that's right.
And his wife Royce.
Just very gracious people, always good to me.
Wally Groff was a guy that I remember at a time when I needed something and it involved athletic tickets because I'd lost some tickets my dad had sent me.
And I just went over and pleaded my case to Wally Groff, and he took the time and listened to me and shook my hand and took care of me.
That was a big deal to me.
And he was then the ticket manager?
He was actually the athletic business manager is what he was, yes.
And I just remember that.
Harry Green was the assistant or associate executive director of the then Aggie Club and had come to Laredo and given a speech.

with Buck and I went by to see him when I was in school and he encouraged me to get involved in the then student Aggie Club and I did and ultimately became the first president of that organized group in 1978 and 79 and that was a great experience for me.
It provided me with some leadership opportunities.
So Harry was a good guy to know.
Anyone else?
Oh, I'm sure there are.
I could probably go on and on and on.
As you look back, how did, how well did A&M prepare you for the real world of employment and so forth?
How did, did A&M play any role in your getting a job?
Yes, it did.
An Aggie hired me out of A&M by the name of Ned Bruin, who was with Hughes Tool Company.
No interview.
All he said was, what do you want to work?

And I don't know if it was because he knew my dad or he was a member of the class of 45 or he had been exposed to me when I was a student in some of my leadership roles, but I interviewed with several companies and Ned Bruin finally told me, he says, you're coming to work for me.
Qualities of being an Aggie.
What is an Aggie?
The first thing that comes to mind is just a level of honesty, even when it's not the most flattering.
I have been just impressed my entire life in associating with Aggies who
No matter what the situation, honesty is the preeminent characteristic that they all display.
And that's an endearing quality, even when it's, as I say, not very flattering to the individual or the situation or to Texas A&M.
Just to know that people can be honest.
Other qualities?
Obviously pride.
I've talked about that already.
Sometimes that's a dangerous thing.
It can get you in trouble when you're a little clouded in your emotions of pride about an institution like A&M.
But it's certainly a characteristic that I think the outside world attributes to Texas Aggies.
I'd have to say that in my experience as executive director now and traveling around with my peers, the attribute that they
Thank you.

usually associate with Texas Aggies is tremendous pride and I think that's a great quality to have if you have pride in your school I bet you got pride in yourself to start with so you couple that with the honesty and I think the integrity and the old you know the Aggie philosophy of Aggies don't lie cheat or steal or tolerate those who do I hope carries on for forever do Aggies care much about your ancestry oh yes indeed
And wait, I'm talking about what country your ancestors came from.
Oh, I don't know about that.
I was thinking more, you know, where you came from and so on.
I don't know.
You know, I really haven't examined that, Haskell.
Actually, I think of Aggies as being inclusive in terms of that doesn't matter.
Your dad was rich and mine was poor, so what?
No, no.
That sort of thing.
As you were preparing to leave the campus with your degree, what kind of world did you think you were entering and how well prepared did you feel you were because of A&M?
You know, I felt more prepared while I was a student than when I walked across that stage with that tube in my hand and sat back down in my seat and it just hit me.
And I said, oh my God, what?
Now.
And you just think of things that A&M probably didn't prepare you for.
Filling out your own tax form.
Now you graduated in spring?
December of 79.
December of 79.
Yeah, December of 79.
Michael Halboody was my commencement speaker.

uh describe uh who came and how you how the family my mother didn't come is what i remember most she was ill my father came and and my only aunt my father's sister came my sister my oldest sister and my well both my sisters came and uh a cousin was here i just felt a lot of support i'm sad my mother couldn't be there interesting relative to ed cooper
who took, I want to say, a very sincere interest in me during my days at A&M, and I know monitored my progress without me knowing it.

He set up a little graduation party at his house for me and told me that when I walked across the stage and he shook my hand and, oh, I can't remember, the interim president, Jarvis Miller, handed me my tube, that my diploma would not be in there.
He said, don't panic.
Your diploma will not be in there.
And I said, OK, but what does that mean?
He said, well, you'll find out.
So that was in G. Raleigh, Wyne.
And I was a little panicked.
I was worried that maybe something had happened and I didn't know about it.
My whole family was here.
And we took pictures after the ceremony.
We were all outside having a big time.
And then, of course, we were supposed to go over to Mr. Cooper's.
And I thought we were just going to go over and have
you know, a picnic or something.
Well, he had a full-blown meal for family and guests and at an appropriate point gathered everybody's attention and had a nice big tube and he said some nice things about me.
and said, you know, Porter's not going to impress anybody with his GPA, but he's going to be a success in life because of all that he represents.
Anyway, he just said some nice things about me and then proceeded to pull my diploma out of the tube.
And he said, this was hand signed by Jarvis Miller,
this week, and he said, and now I'm going to hand sign it in front of all of you.
And so that meant a lot to me.
That meant a lot to me.
And that's one of my real fond memories of A&M.
See, now I think commencement done the way we do it here is another one of those key bonding events.
Indeed.
I think it's having a little bit of a metamorphosis right now, that we've moved to Reed Arena, and it's undergoing a bit of an evolution like other big schools have gone under for years.
But we still have more of a cohesive atmosphere around commencement than most schools.
See, at Missouri, I had great trouble, first of all, getting the deans to agree that we would have an institutional commencement.
They wanted to have their own in their place.
And they didn't want to call out each name.
And only about a third of the students would even show up.
And those who did, when they got their diploma, they walked straight out of the building and their family walked out.
So it wasn't at all a positive.
But if we can keep aware that everybody goes through, it's like Bonfire or anything else, where we're all part of the same feeling, I think that's very, very important.
Let's see, and you said you felt quite well prepared.
We're getting ready now to end this.
What if someone came up to you and gave you a check for a million dollars with one condition on it?
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you get to decide how that money would be used.
If you could make a momentous gift to A&M, for what purpose would you want it used?

Well, the first thing I'd do is make sure the Association of Former Students brokered that gift because this is the only organization that I know of that touches 43,000 students, 2,500 faculty and administrators, and does an array of so many good things for so many people.
It would be an easy and quick decision to say, do what is best for Texas A&M with this money and not tie it to some selfish interest on my behalf.
Okay.
And then a request, if you have any Aggie memorabilia
letters, papers, journals, at some point, for goodness sakes, be sure that it is preserved either by this organization or by the A&M Archives.
I've preached that sermon to a number of people, particularly to a lady whose husband was an important president here who still has them at her house.
Oh, gosh, yes.
And Ann and everybody else is trying to persuade Mrs. Rutter to
And she's not doing it.
And people are walking away with them.
She'll hand them.
Ann says strangers will drive up, sweet-talk Mrs. Rutter, and they'll walk away with a letter signed by MacArthur or a letter signed by Patton.
And I'm saying, oh, oh, oh, how priceless those would be.
Okay, last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M?

my vocabulary is just not big enough Haskell because of what A&M and I know you've heard this from countless Aggies you've interviewed because of what A&M has done for me that I'll never be able to repay and in some form or fashion service is a lot of my repayment but I just can't imagine what kind of citizen what kind of
husband, father, what kind of person I'd be had I not gone to A&M.
Had I made that decision to go to the University of Texas or to Texas Tech,
I don't think, I'm pretty sure I wouldn't be the person I am today.

Even though I had a tremendous upbringing and a foundation for being successful in life by virtue of my parents' efforts, A&M put the finishing touches on me and introduced me to a level of pride that I transferred to myself.
And I think that's been the difference in my life.
That's a good place.
